{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513234"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12065"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12065"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.77,0.06,0.06,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78422"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4627"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2022-09-07T18:30:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T18:25:31+10:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-09-16T17:42:26+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-17 09:43:00"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12065"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9435"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"5197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63784"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3526"},{"type":"tags","id":"3527"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7051"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26781"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63784"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78422"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the clinic for the evaluation of hypercalcaemia of 3.22 mmol/L (\u003Cem\u003E2.25-2.62\u003C/em\u003E). This was found incidentally on a laboratory test panel that was drawn during hospitalisation for cervical spondy\u00adlosis. Despite fluid administration in the hospital, her serum calcium at discharge was 2.94 mmol/L (\u003Cem\u003E2.25-2.62\u003C/em\u003E). The patient is asymptomatic. Otherwise, she is in good health and has had her recommended age-appropriate cancer screening. She denies constipation or bone pain and is now eight weeks out from her spinal surgery. Today, her serum calcium level is 3.09mmol/L (\u003Cem\u003E2.25-2.62\u003C/em\u003E), and phosphate is 0.74 mmol/L (\u003Cem\u003E0.97-1.45\u003C/em\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E). Her haematocrit and all other standard haematological and biochemical tests, including creatinine, are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the hypercalcaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Granulomatous disease","Primary hyperparathyroidism","Milk-alkali syndrome","Malignancy","Immobilisation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPrimary hyperparathyroidism and malignancy account for over 90% of cases of hypercalcaemia. In asymptomatic patients, \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary hyperparathyroidism \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most common cause. In patients admitted to the hospital with symptomatic hypercalcaemia, malignancy is the most common cause. Primary hyperparathyroidism results from the autonomous secretion of parathyroid hormone (PTH) that is no longer regulated by serum calcium levels, usually related to the development of parathyroid adenomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost patients are asymptomatic or have minimal symptoms at the time of diagnosis. Testing of the intact parathyroid hormone level is the core of the diagnosis. An elevated intact parathyroid hormone level with an elevated serum calcium level is diagnostic of primary hyperparathyroidism. Calcium is regulated in bone, the gastrointestinal tract and the kidney. Other causes of increased bone turnover include Paget\u2019s disease, \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmobilisation,\u003C/strong\u003E hyperthyroidism, hypervitaminosis A and adrenal insufficiency. Causes of increased GI absorption include vitamin D intoxication and \u003Cstrong\u003Emilk-alkali syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. Hypervitaminosis D can either be from overdose or endogenous production by granulomatous disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary hyperparathyroidism (PHPT) is the most common cause of hypercalcemia in the outpatient setting.a","It results from abnormal regulation and excessive release of parathyroid hormone (PTH) from one or more of the parathyroid glands."],"references":["Dandurand K, Ali DS, Khan AA. Primary Hyperparathyroidism: A Narrative Review of Diagnosis and Medical Management. J Clin Med. 2021 Apr 9;10(8):1604. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33918966/","Pokhrel B, Leslie SW, Levine SN. Primary Hyperparathyroidism. 2024 Mar 1. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722924. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28722924/","Walker MD, Silverberg SJ. Primary hyperparathyroidism. Nat Rev Endocrinol. 2018 Feb;14(2):115-125. doi: 10.1038/nrendo.2017.104. Epub 2017 Sep 8. PMID: 28885621; PMCID: PMC6037987. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28885621/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63784"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12065"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63784"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T18:25:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T18:25:59+10:30","number":5,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-01-10T18:25:31+10:30","plagiarismScore":51.1,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4627-5.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T033702Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=c6e6a9657c35f4bbf091ee582162083950e9a474f9c85d40a82a570c1488ce71"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4627"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78422"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9435"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rela